---++ Argumentation and discourse schemata
   * *Toulmin* (according to Judith's lexicon)
      * <img src="%ATTACHURLPATH%/toulmin_scheme.png" height="250px"/>
      * Conventional transitions that connect _data_(reasons, facts) with _claims_(conclusions) are formed by a _warrant_. 
        A warrant certifies that the presented data are really suitable to support the claim.
      * These conventions are supported by the _backing_
         * Typical sources of the backing 'Gesetze, Normen, Regeln, Prinzipien, Allgemeine Tatsachen, Anerkannte Bestimmungen, Anerkannte Erfahrungen, Bedürfnisse, Taxonomische Klassifikationen'
         * "In der Alltagsargumentation dagegen bleibt einem [...] häufig nichts anderes übrig, als den Übergang von Argument (Daten) zur Schlussfolgerung (Konklusion) [...] durch Appelle an den mehr oder weniger gesunden Menschenverstand" zu stützen.
      * Exceptional conditions under which the claim will not hold are called _rebuttal_ ([[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counterargument][Wikipedia]]
      * (Modal) _qualifiers_ may reduce the degree of certainty that the author puts in his arguments.
      * [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toulmin_method][Wiki: Toulmin Method]]
      * [[http://www.teachsam.de/deutsch/d_rhetorik/argu/arg_mod_toul_4.htm][Example: Stephan ist ein guter Schüler]]
   * *argumentum* (Latin rethoric, according to Judith's lexicon)
      * Principles of proving/procedures: _a. exclusionis_, _a. e contrario_: prove that the counterclaim is false, _a. fortiori_: proof by concluding from already proven claims, _a. ex concesso_: (similar to previous), proof by concluding from already acknowledged claim, _a. negativum_
      * Categorization based on sentence structure: _a. priori_ vs. _a. posteri_
      * Categorization based on refered instance: _a. ad hominem_, _a. ad rem_, _a. ad iudicium_, ...
   * *Swale's CARS* model (territory->find niche->occupy niche; Swales: Genre Analysis, Cambridge Uni. Press, 1990)
   * *Teufel's CARS* (sentence classification into background, own, aim, textual, contrast, basis, other; Teufel,Carletta,Moens: An Annotation Scheme for Discourse-Level Argumentation in Research, EACL 1999, 110-117)
   * Hyland's metadiscourse schema (Persuasion and Context: The Pragmatics of Academic Metadiscourse, Journal of Pragmatics 30, 1990, 437-455)
   * *ScholOnto/ClaiMaker*
      * [[http://projects.kmi.open.ac.uk/scholonto/docs/VizNetArg2002.pdf]]


---++ Paper summaries

---+++ Recognizing Arguing Subjectivity and Argument Tags

   * Field: "arguing subjectivity"
   * Dataset: blog posts and open editorial entries dealing with "ObamaCare"
   * Annotation unit: Argument="... spans of 1 sentence or less in which a writer 'conveys a controversial private state concerning what she believes to be true or what action she believes should be taken'
   * In political science, there seems to be some kind of "arguing dimension"
   * Features: "investigate the utility of a sentiment lexicon, discourse parser, and semantic similarity measures with respect to recognizing arguments."
       * Discourse? Discourse parser by Lin, using Penn Discourse TreeBank (PDTB) tagset. (Lin et al., Automatically evaluating text coherence using discourse relations.),
       * Sentiment score? Lexicon with lemmas being marked as strong/weak. Mark sentence if num. of words with strong(weak) sent. score is two(three) or more (Theresa Wilson. 2005. Recognizing contextual polarity in phrase-level sentiment analysis. In EMNLP, pages 347354.)

---+++ Automatic extraction of knowledge from student essays
   * survey of annotation schemes
   * presents a lot of argumentation schemes


   
   

---++ High-school material
   * [[http://lehrerfortbildung-bw.de/faecher/deutsch/gym/fb1/02_komp_unterricht/04_diagnose/4_argument/][Einfaches Argumentieren]] ([[http://lehrerfortbildung-bw.de/faecher/deutsch/gym/fb1/02_komp_unterricht/04_diagnose/4_argument/017_eingdiagn_argument7.pdf][pdf]])
      * Terminology: These,Argument,Folgerung
      * Argumentation cues: denn,weil,nämlich,auch,zum Beispiel/beispielsweise
      * Sentence structure: Wenn ... , dann...
      * Classification for argumentation level: A,B,C
   *  [[http://do.nw.schule.de/jgrdo-medien/li_leiste/faecher/de/7/argumentieren/argumentieren_schulbeginn.htm][Argumentieren in der Klasse 7c 2006/07]]
      * Ask the 6 "W" questions: Who,What,When,Where,Why,How
      * [[http://do.nw.schule.de/jgrdo-medien/li_leiste/faecher/de/7/argumentieren/sanduhr.pdf][Sanduhr]]: gutes Argument = Behauptung+Begründung+Beweis
      * Subjectivity cues: "Ich finde", "Meiner Meinung nach", "Ich will"
      * Conclusion/cause cues: "So [VV.*]", "Jedoch", "Durch NP-action VP NP-result", "Falls/Wenn ... , dann"
   * [[http://www.digitale-schule-bayern.de/ds.py?sid=a042f94e44516405bf&_controller=DSController2&schreibformen_78_sparte_hmid=20&faecherid=30&themaid=585][Example Discussions]]
      * Sequences: erstens,zweitens,(nicht) zuletzt, schließlich
   * [[http://www.unterrichtsmaterial-schule.de/deutschvorschau67.shtml][So schreibt man eine Argumentation]]
      * General argumentation scheme:
         * One topic/thesis is supported by several arguments
         * Each argument may be supported by additional facts/examples/observations ("Beleg")
      * Idiomatic expressions (Blatt 3):
         * Introduction: "Immer wieder", "Es ist wichtig, dass", "Nur wenige"
         * Argumentation: "Dafür spricht", "Dagegen spricht", "Gegen ... spricht", "Hinzu kommt", "Darüber hinaus", "Zusätzlich (ist festzustellen, dass)", "Allerdings (muss man auch sehen, dass)", "Man darf auch nicht übersehen/vergessen", "Entscheidend ist", "Beleg dafür ist", "spielt eine wichtige Rolle", "hauptsächlich"
         * Conclusion: "abschließend" ("schließlich",...), "(vertritt den) Standpunkt(, dass)"
   * [[http://www.lehrerfreund.de/schule/1s/ueberleitung-argumente/2662][Überleitung zwischen Argumenten]]
      * long list of connectives (support, contradiction, emphasis)


